  "original_title": "Sri Lanka\u2019s Chevron Lubricants net up 82-pct despite forex loss",
  "text_idx": {
    "en": {
      "title": "Sri Lanka\u2019s Chevron Lubricants net up 82-pct despite forex loss",
      "author": "",
      "body_lines": [
        "ECONOMYNEXT \u2013 Profits at Sri Lanka\u2019s Chevron Lubricants grew 82 percent from a year ago to 839 million rupees in the June 2022 quarter interim accounts showed as inflation rose 50 percent in the year to June and a soft-peg with the US dollar collapsed.",
        "The firm reported earnings of 3.50 rupees for the quarter.  The stock closed at 78 rupees down 20 cents.",
        "The first quarter of 2021 was also hit by a Coronavirus pandemic.",
        "Gross profits grew 191 percent to 2.87 billion rupees, with revenues up 124 percent to 6.1 billion rupees and cost of sales grew 86 percent to 3.2 billion rupees.",
        "Finance costs rose to 1.2 billion rupees from 22 million rupees as the rupee collapsed in the worst currency crisis in the history of the island\u2019s intermediate regime central bank after two year of money printing.",
        "Chevron had imported lubricants on credit and had been hit as the rupee collapsed.",
        "\u201cDue to the acute foreign currency liquidity shortage in the Country\u2019s banking system, the Company carried a considerable proportion of USD denominated Trade and other payables, which were being settled based on availability of USD through its Banks,\u201d the company said.",
        "Sri Lanka\u2019s inflation in the year to June 2022 had shot up to 50 percent officially but most companies had steeply raised prices as costs rose. (Colombo/July29/2022)"
      ],
